[PERSON_NAME]. I specialize in sports (I am currently writing a book on [PERSON_NAME] and MJ), and politics. I am part-owner of a gym, and have been a certified personal trainer for 15 years, so I am comfortable writing about fitness. I have written artist statements and bios for clients.

My father, brother and I make custom humidors, so I have substantial knowledge of, and have built great connections in, the cigar industry. 

Basically, I am pretty comfortable writing about a wide array of subjects.

I would normally charge around $100-$150 per article (most can be written and edited in 2 or 3 hours). I average about $55/hr on copywriting services, so that is where I get my range. 

Please let me know if you have any other questions.

Shorter articles can certainly be written in an hour, in which case, my rate would be $50.

As far as deadlines go, I work mostly from home now, and am transitioning into a full-time writing career. What that path looks like is to to be determined, but is taking shape, but we (myself, wife and two young kids) have determined it is best for me to take advantage of the opportunities before me as a writer. I have taken more of an advisory role in our gym, as well as in our humidor business; so deadlines are not a problem.

On music, I am very close with [PERSON_NAME] (known as [PERSON_NAME]), and am also possibly partnering with him in the near future on certain projects.

To elaborate on politics and religion: I am a [PERSON_NAME] who leans to the middle-right, but I do enjoy, provocatively, about the hypocrisy on both sides of the aisle. I have no problem writing objectively about either subject, but there are probably a few aspects of each I feel more comfortable writing about than others.

For fiction, I am all over the map, but have been greatly influenced by [PERSON_NAME] on the craft of writing (not in quirky Horror, just in style), and I do enjoy Spy Novels.

But at my heart, I am creative in both fiction and non-fiction. I have no interest in writing bland articles. I enjoy inserting a &quotewow-factor&quote whenever necessary...if, in fact, it is necessary.
*[PERSON_NAME], not the former mlb manager

I normally like to charge hourly, because research varies based on the subject matter. I can write about basketball in my sleep, yet an article about the pros and cons of both [PERSON_NAME] and [PERSON_NAME]'s budgets might take a bit more research. But I am willing to set a per word rate that I think can account for the different variables. Perhaps staying in the neighborhood of 25 cents per word will accomplish that. That way if he takes me an hour and a half or two to write a 250-word article on heavy-research subject matter, I could possibly balance that with a half-hour or 45-minute effort in writing a 250-word piece on [PERSON_NAME].

It's never going to be an exact science, and I understand that dynamic. But I think the 25 cent neighborhood gives me some wiggle room that I can be comfortable with.

If it just needs a pin to reconnect the extension hinge, that's super simple, and I'd feel dumb or mean charging you anything for that repair. 

If that extension hinge is broken, I may need to take it home and rebuild it a little. But still, it's not a big deal.  I'd charge no more than $30 to rebuild it and reinstall it. 

Something to keep in mind, is the age of your piano.  Be careful with your technician, because they can find lots of new problems and want to charge you more.  

I believe that piano is an early 1900s Upright piano.  They are still very popular piano's because of their gorgeous wooden cabinet exterior.  However, the challenge with that age of piano is that the piano manufacturers went out of business a long time ago.  And replacement parts don't exists anymore.  So, anything that is broken, has to be repaired or rebuilt.  And also, because of its old age we'll need to work on it very very carefully.  The strings are most likely oxidized and now somewhat brittle, so tightening them to correct the pitch can sometimes cause them to break. And the large action that throws the hammers against the stings, is most likely starting to disintegrate, resulting in sticky keys or keys that don't work, because they're not hitting the string anymore. 

So just be aware that costs can skyrocket if you don't have a defined price quote and define scope of work.

Hey Crystal,

From one veteran to another, I appreciate and sympathize!  We will apply a 10% on any package of your choice.

The training we offer would propell you to the next level.  I imagine you wanting your dog as a service dog, not just an emotional support dog.  Our training specifically focuses on communication, not correction, and build mental focus.  We start at square one/recall/come and sit, which you will find is 80% of your dogs life. :) You would specifically work on getting him to drown out the world around him so he pays attention to you. 

Second lesson: Place! Hold a position on anything with a visual barrier that is safe for your dog to sit on. Impulse control exercise and confidence builder.  Huge for service dogs!

Third lesson: Heel! How to walk next to me with zero tension on the leash, and I mean zero! You will have the ability to communicate with your dog regardless of what's going on which is so important!

My husband and I were both dog handlers in the Air Force.  Let me be the first to tell you that ecollar training is the most humane way to train!  Ultimately, you shouldn't want to use any tool if you have the kind of dog that responds to positive only methods.  

I would encourage you to come and do lessons with me at my house versus at the office or your home.  Reason being:  I need to train you as well and unless I put you both into real life situations, we will be stuck in our advancement, make sense? :) Plus, it saves you an additional $200.
